ETI_Unknown_ceo_review_52_0,ETI,ETI,Banking,Unknown,manual_pdf,ceo_review,"In the fourth quarter of 2025, as part of our measures to exit the Central Bank of Nigeria's regulatory forbearance, we took significant impairments in Nigeria, particularly within the CIB portfolio. This resulted in a pre-tax loss of $31 million for the year and a non-performing loan ratio of 42.1%. These actions made the turnaround more demanding in the near term, but they were necessary. They brought greater transparency to legacy issues and allowed us to address the difficult matters directly rather than carry them forward.",86,good,,,,,,,,pending
ETI_Unknown_ceo_review_53_0,ETI,ETI,Banking,Unknown,manual_pdf,ceo_review,"What matters now is execution. We are working closely with the regulator. We are actively managing capital and asset-quality issues and we are reshaping the business towards areas where we see better-quality growth. That shift is already visible. In 2025, CCB in Nigeria grew by 23% year on year, driven by deeper client engagement and growing transaction volumes. We still have work to do, but the path is clear: deal with the legacy issues, restore compliance, and build a better-quality business underneath.",82,good,,,,,,,,pending
